When you change ORT's implementation to kMSDomain, did you also change the custom op in onnx model to kMSDomain? You need to add kMSDomain to ModelProto.opset_import, and add domain to the NodeProto of the custom op.

This is why you should not change op schema in onnx. For manipulating onnx model in Python, please check onnx's [PythonAPIOverview.md](https://github.com/onnx/onnx/blob/master/docs/PythonAPIOverview.md).

You may also find some Python code in test to check or change [opset_import](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/8d737f977056444a307f1b7f0bcd402fba62d790/docs/python/inference/examples/plot_profiling.py#L20-L27), or create node in [kMSDomain](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/8d737f977056444a307f1b7f0bcd402fba62d790/onnxruntime/test/python/contrib_ops/onnx_test_trilu.py#L22-L27).

```
import onnx
graph = gs.import_onnx(onnx.load("aslfeatv2_op11.onnx"))

                  'ExtractImagePatches_3', 'ExtractImagePatches_4', 'ExtractImagePatches_5']
to_remove_nodes={}
for t_name in target_name_list:
    to_remove_nodes[t_name] = [node for node in graph.nodes if node.name == t_name ][0]
count=0
to_remove_nodes_list=[]
for k in to_remove_nodes:
    target_node=to_remove_nodes[k]
    to_remove_nodes_list.append(target_node)  # ExtractImagePatches
    to_remove_nodes_list.append(target_node.i())  # # Reshape
    to_remove_nodes_list.append(target_node.i().i())  # Mul
    to_remove_nodes_list.append(target_node.i().i().i())  # Reshape
    to_remove_nodes_list.append(target_node.i().i().i().i()) # Reshape
    to_remove_nodes_list.append(target_node.i().i().i().i().i())# Range
    to_remove_nodes_list.append(target_node.i().i().i().i().i().o())  # Range->Size
    to_remove_nodes_list.append(target_node.i().i().i().i().i().o().o())  # Range->Size
    to_remove_nodes_list.append(target_node.i().i().i().i().i().o().o().o())  # Range->Size
    to_remove_nodes_list.append(target_node.o())  # Reshape
    to_remove_nodes_list.append(target_node.o().o())  # Cast
    if count%2:
        ASLFeatPlugin_node = gs.Node(op="ASLFeatPluginY", attrs=target_node.attrs)
        ASLFeatPlugin_node.name = 'ASLFeatPluginY' + str(count)
    else:
        ASLFeatPlugin_node = gs.Node(op="ASLFeatPluginX", attrs=target_node.attrs)
        ASLFeatPlugin_node.name = 'ASLFeatPluginX' + str(count)
    ASLFeatPlugin_node.inputs.append(target_node.i().i().i().i().i().i(1).i().i().i().i().i().outputs[0]) # Pad
    node_add_out = target_node.o().o().o()  # [node for node in graph.nodes if node.name == 'add_4'][0]
    ASLFeatPlugin_node.outputs.append(node_add_out.inputs[0])
    tmp_var_to_remain = node_add_out.inputs[1]  # Cast

    node_add_out.inputs.append(tmp_var_to_remain)
    node_add_out.inputs.append(ASLFeatPlugin_node.outputs[0])
    graph.nodes.append(ASLFeatPlugin_node)
    if count % 2:

        to_remove_nodes_list = []

#####################

M_P_0=gs.Constant(name="pad_0", values=np.asarray([3, 3, 3, 3]))
mirror_pad_node_0.attrs['mode']='constant'
mirror_pad_node_0.inputs.pop()
mirror_pad_node_0.inputs.append(M_P_0)

mirror_pad_node_1 = [node for node in graph.nodes if node.name == 'MirrorPad_1' ][0]
```

Per Pad opset 11 [spec](https://github.com/onnx/onnx/blob/master/docs/Changelog.md#inputs-2---3-9):

pads : tensor(int64)
Tensor of integers indicating the number of padding elements to add or remove (if negative) at the beginning and end of each axis. For 2D input tensor, it is the number of pixels. `pads` should be a 1D tensor of shape [2 * input_rank]. `pads` format should be: [x1_begin, x2_begin,...,x1_end, x2_end,...], where xi_begin is the number of pad values added at the beginning of axis `i` and xi_end, the number of pad values added at the end of axis `i`.

I wonder how to check the custom ops's output by calling cudaMemcpy DeviceToHost? is there some wrapper API?

There are ways you can continue debugging. In the custom op implementation's Compute() method, you can do a cudaDeviceSync before doing a cudaMemcpy to host of the op's inputs and making sure the inputs look okay by inspecting it. If the input looks okay, launch your cuda kernel, do a device sync again and do a cudaMemcpy to host of the op's output and inspect its contents.

But before this, I would first create a single node onnx model containing your custom op alone and run it with different test cases (just like the tests here in the file) and ensure your op's implementation is correct.

By the way, are using the same compute stream for launching your custom kernel as the stream used by inference session ? The test code shows how you can create a cuda stream, pass it to the session for use by ORT's CUDA kernel and you can use the same stream to launch your custom kernel - this should sync the execution between ORT's CUDA kernels and your custom kernel implicitly. Check here- https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/27e778909d75d0d7ff1177f3e86ef8c19db71d5d/onnxruntime/test/shared_lib/custom_op_utils.cc#L35

Hope this helps

